<p>Other methods for the detection ooration: none;" href="http://www.mlo-online.com/articles/201311/images/Education-Viraclinics-sample.png" target="_Blank">Click here to view a larger vf antiviral resistant viruses include phenotypic assays.<sup>17</sup> Phenotypic resistance tests have the advantage of detecting all potential resistant strains, while genotyping assays will detect only previously described resistant strains, as they require prior knowledge of which mutations in the viral genome induce resistance. On the other hand, sensitivity of virus culture required for phenotyping resistance is low at later time points during infection when resistance may occur. Phenotypic resistance may further be underestimated when resistant strains are present as minority species, or when they are compromised in their <em>in vitro</em> replication kinetics, e.g., as clearly shown for H3N2 292K oseltamivir resistant strains.<sup>18,19</sup></p>
<p><strong>Aims of diagnostic testing</strong></p>
<p>The majority of patients with respiratory illness suspected for influenza virus infection at the offices of general practitioners and general hospitals are uncomplicated patients who are very likely to recover with minimal intervention by physicians. Interventions on the basis of results of a testing algorithm are therefore relatively minor with respect to the outcome of the infection. Influenza virus-infected patients with pneumonia are often given antibiotic treatment because Pneumococcal and/or <em>Staphylococcus aureus</em> infection can usually not orithm are therefore relatively minor with respect to the outcome of the infection. Influenza virus-infected patients with pneumonia are often given abe ruled out.<sup>20</sup> Rapid tests for influenza are well suited for this purpose.</p>
<p>It should be kept in mind, however, that a physician&rsquo;s clinical diagnosis based on seasonality and influenza-specific symptoms without <em>in vitro</em> diagnostics has a positive predictive value around 60%, and the addition of a rapid test result will increase this percentage only to around 80%. In academic and general hospitals with sufficient capacity for quarantining patients, influenza virus- and RSV-infected patients may be separately isolated from other patients to prevent nosocomial transmission. It may be argued that rapid tests are also sufficient for this purpose because RT-PCR diagnosed patients missed by rapid tests often carry low viral loads and may not easily transmit virus. Most laboratories will, however, offer fast RT-PCR- based panel testing to prevent misinterpretation of rapid test results.</p>
<p>Patients with an increased risk for developing severe disease, such as children with underlying disease and immunocompromised patients, are in general referred to hospitals with high expertise both in the clinical setting and in the laboratory. The diagnostic test armamentarium of routine diagnostic laboratories serving these hospitals requires assays that enable monitoring of the influenza viral load during antiviral treatment. Viral load ase both in the clinical setting and in the laboratory. The diagnostic test armamentarium of routine diagnostic laboratories serving these hospitals reqsays may further be used to estimate which pathogen is the causative agent when multiple pathogens are detected in a patient. Both quantitative culture and real-time RT-PCR give quantitative results. Interpretation and technical performance of such tests require a high level of expertise. The advantage of quantitative culture over real-time RT-PCR is its ability to give information on the amount of infectious virus particles, while real-time RT-PCR detects both infectious and non-infectious virus particles as well as viral breakdown products. Especially in intubated patients with serious lung damage, very high viral loads may be detected by real-time RT-PCR in lower respiratory tract samples that cannot be cultured, in which resistance often does not develop despite long-term persistence, and therefore may be non-infectious viral debris.<sup>21</sup></p>
<p>Quantitative culture is, however, relatively expensive and time-consuming and requires high-level expertise for even the most academic diagnostic laboratories. These assays are therefore for diagnostic purposes, in general only performed in the context of clinical trials. A clear example in which quantitative culture may have significant benefit is clinical trials with antivirals, such as favipiravirs, which increase the production of non-infectious particles.<sup>22</sup> In clinical trials with antivirf clinical trials. A clear example in which quantitative culture may have significant benefit is clinical trials with antivirals, such as favipiravirsals that directly inhibit virus production, quantitative culture may give information on the duration of infectious virus shedding and the ability to reduce transmissibility. Given the fact that data generated on a limited number of patients in a clinical trial has a significant impact on the health of large numbers of patients when a drug is licensed, relatively expensive assays requiring a high level of expertise that provide important information on antiviral drug potency and resistance development, including quantitative real time RT-PCR, quantitative culture and even NGS, are needed and likely to be cost-effective. In summary, the various levels of influenza diagnostics applied in different settings are illustrated in <strong>Figure 2</strong>.</p>
